In .NET MAUI, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
            }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- `AddAndroid` exposes the full Android `Activity` lifecycle (`OnCreate`, `OnResume`, `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnDestroy`, etc.).
- `AddiOS` exposes UIKit `UIApplicationDelegate` events (`DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.).
- The delegate parameter (e.g., `activity`, `application`) gives you the native platform object if you need it.
